    "summary": [
      "A decade after representatives from 196 countries gathered at Le Bourget, France to sign the Paris Agreement on December 12, 2015, global temperatures in 2024 reached 1.45°C above pre-industrial levels, dangerously close to the threshold.",
      "According to the Sixth Assessment Report of the IPCC and warnings by Dr. Friederike Otto from the Grantham Institute at Imperial College London, corrective action windows are rapidly closing as fossil fuel use remains high despite renewable energy expansion in countries like Germany, China, and the United States.",
      "The Global Carbon Project reported a record 37.4 gigaton CO₂ emission in 2023 under professor Pierre Friedlingstein's leadership at the University of Exeter, while the International Energy Agency noted that coal usage in South and Southeast Asia partly offset gains elsewhere.",
      "At COP30 scheduled for November 2025 in Belém, Brazil, UN Secretary-General António Guterres urged countries to submit updated Nationally Determined Contributions with more ambitious targets by 2035, as experts like Dr. Katharine Hayhoe from The Nature Conservancy and Texas Tech University emphasized the need for political will."
    ],
